Preheat your oven to 200°C. Chop the @cauliflower{1/2} into florets (like small trees!), pop the 
florets in a #bowl and season with @salt{to taste} and @ground black pepper{to taste}. Drizzle with 
@oil{for roasting}, then sprinkle on the @ground turmeric{2%tsp} and half the @nigella seeds{1}. 
Toss to distribute all the flavours evenly. Roast on a #baking tray{} until soft and golden, 
~{20-25%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1/2}. Roughly chop the @coriander{1/2}(roughly 
chopped, stalks and all). Trim the @green beans{150}(trimmed and chopped into thirds). Heat a splash 
of @oil{splash} in a #large saucepan{} on medium heat. Add the onion and cook until soft, 
~{5-6%minutes}, stirring occasionally. Add the @easy garlic{1/2} and @Goan Xacuti Spice{1}. Cook 
for ~{1%minute} more.

Stir in the @tomatoes{1}(finely chopped) and the @vegetable stock powder{1}. Add the 
@red split lentils{100} and @water{250}(for the dal). Stir to dissolve the stock powder. Bring 
to a gentle simmer, cover with a #lid (or some foil) and leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}. Stir 
occasionally to make sure the lentils aren't catching.

While the dal is bubbling away, heat a #frying pan{} over medium heat (no oil!). Add the 
@flaked almonds{15} and remaining nigella seeds. Cook until the almonds are golden, 
~{4-5%minutes}. Stir frequently and watch them like a hawk, they burn easily! When done, keep 
to one side.

Once the lentil mix has been cooking for 10 mins, remove the #lid and stir in the green beans. 
Cook uncovered until the beans are tender and the lentils cooked, ~{10-12%minutes}.

> Don't worry if the dal is drying out a little – just add a bit more water to get a looser consistency.

When the beans are cooked and the lentils are mushy, remove from the heat. Stir through half of 
the coriander and season with salt and pepper to taste. Serve the dal in #bowls{}, top with the 
cauliflower florets. Top with dollops of @Greek style natural yoghurt{112.5%g} and finish with 
a sprinkle of almonds, nigella seeds and coriander. Enjoy!

> The humble dal is a great example of a body-nourishing, warming dish that stands out in taste.